Capstone Project: Exploration¶

Machine Learning Engineer Nanodegree¶

Manceñido Agustín, 2019¶

In this section, the dataset will be analyzed to understand how each feature is related to the others, consider the importance of each feature and find out which are actually relevant for understanding the price of the product. Then the data will preprocess to create a better representation of price by performing a scaling and detecting (and removing if needed) outliers to obtain significant and meaningful results and get the prices related to the best sellers.

Notes:

  • For the bechmarks models used as baseline for this project, please refer to the Capstone benchmarks file.
  • For the complete final model and results, please refer to the Capstone exploration file.

Step 1: Functions¶

In [4]:
# Plot generators

def display_side_by_side(*args):
    html_str=''
    for df in args:
        html_str+=df.to_html()
    display_html(html_str.replace('table ','table style="display:inline "'),raw=True)
    
def _generate_bar_plot_hor(df, col, title, color, w=None, h=None, lm=0, limit=100, need_trace = False):
    cnt_srs = df[col].value_counts()[:limit]
    trace = go.Bar(y=cnt_srs.index[::-1], x=cnt_srs.values[::-1], orientation = 'h',
        marker=dict(color=color))
    if need_trace:
        return trace
    layout = dict(title=title, yaxis={'type': 'category'}, margin=dict(l=lm), width=w, height=h)
    data = [trace]
    fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
    iplot(fig)

def _generate_bar_plot_ver(df, col, title, color, w=None, h=None, lm=0, limit=100, need_trace = False):
    cnt_srs = df[col].value_counts()[:limit]
    trace = go.Bar(x=list(cnt_srs.index), y=list(cnt_srs.values),
        marker=dict(color = color))
    if need_trace:
        return trace
    if w != None and h != None:
        layout = dict(title=title, margin=dict(l=lm), width=w, height=h)
    else:
        layout = dict(title=title, margin=dict(l=lm))
    data = [trace]
    fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
    iplot(fig)
    
def _aggregate(df, base_col, agg_col, agg_func, return_trace = False):
    tempdf = df.groupby(base_col).agg({agg_col : agg_func})
    trace = go.Bar(x=tempdf.index, y=tempdf.price, name='', marker=dict(color='#8a7aff'))
    if return_trace:
        return trace
    data = [trace]
    layout = go.Layout(title='', width=500, legend=dict(orientation="h"), margin=dict(b=200))
    fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
    iplot(fig)
    
def _aggregate_bar_plot_hor(df, base_col, agg_col, agg_func, title, color, w=None, h=None, lm=0, limit=100, need_trace = False):
    tempdf = df.groupby(base_col).agg({agg_col : agg_func}).sort_values(agg_col, ascending=False)[:limit]
    trace = go.Bar(y=tempdf.index[::-1], x=tempdf[agg_col][::-1], orientation = 'h', marker=dict(color=color))
    if need_trace:
        return trace
    layout = dict(title=title, yaxis={'type': 'category'}, margin=dict(l=lm), width=w, height=h)
    data = [trace]
    fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
    iplot(fig)

Step 2: Feature Engineering¶

Some feature engineering is performed here by creating new input features from the existing ones. This is often one of the most valuable tasks a data scientist can do to improve model performance and get a better undesrtanding of the information collected.

In [5]:
# FEATURE ENG: Expand date & time features
data = data.copy()
data['created_at'] = pd.to_datetime(data['created_at'])
data['weekday'] = data.created_at.dt.weekday
data['month'] = data.created_at.dt.month
data['day'] = data.created_at.dt.day
data['week'] = data.created_at.dt.week 
data['hour'] = data.created_at.dt.hour 
print "✓ date & time features expanded"

# FEATURE ENG: Add english mapped of weekday
daymap = {0:'Sun', 1:'Mon', 2:'Tue', 3:'Wed', 4:'Thu', 5:'Fri', 6:'Sat'}
data['weekday_en'] = data['weekday'].apply(lambda x : daymap[x])
print "✓ english mapped of weekday added"

# FEATURE ENG: Add title word length
data['title'] = data['title'].fillna(" ")
data['title_len'] = data['title'].apply(lambda x : len(x.split()))
print "✓ title word length added"

# FEATURE ENG: Add earnings
data['earnings'] = data.price * data.sqty
print "✓ earnings added"

# FEATURE ENG: Add state_city
data['state_city'] = data.state +" / "+ data.city
print "✓ state_city added"

# FEATURE ENG: sellers stats
data['best_seller'] = False
data['worst_seller'] = True
print "✓ sellers stats added"

✓ date & time features expanded
✓ english mapped of weekday added
✓ title word length added
✓ earnings added
✓ state_city added
✓ sellers stats added

# Number of elements with most earnings
MAX_EARNS_BST = seller_earn_df.earnings.sum()*BST_SLLR_RATE
MAX_EARNS_WST = seller_earn_df.earnings.sum()*WST_SLLR_RATE
sum_earnings = 0
for index, row in seller_earn_df.iterrows():
    sum_earnings += row.earnings
    data.loc[data['sellerid'] == row.sellerid, 'worst_seller'] = False
    if sum_earnings < MAX_EARNS_BST:
        data.loc[data['sellerid'] == row.sellerid, 'best_seller'] = True
    if sum_earnings > MAX_EARNS_WST:
        print("Worst sellers (earnings): %d / %d." % (index, len(seller_earn_df.index) ))
        break
# Number of elements with most sells
MAX_SELLS_BST = seller_num_df.sells.sum()*BST_SLLR_RATE
MAX_SELLS_WST = seller_num_df.sells.sum()*WST_SLLR_RATE
sum_sells = 0
for index, row in seller_num_df.iterrows():
    sum_sells += row.sells
    data.loc[data['sellerid'] == row.sellerid, 'worst_seller'] = False
    if sum_sells < MAX_SELLS_BST:
        data.loc[data['sellerid'] == row.sellerid, 'best_seller'] = True
    if sum_sells > MAX_SELLS_WST:
        print("Worst sellers (Number of sells): %d / %d." % (index, len(seller_num_df.index) ))
        break

del MAX_EARNS_BST, MAX_EARNS_WST, sum_earnings, MAX_SELLS_BST, MAX_SELLS_WST, sum_sells

In [19]:
# Number of elements with most earnings per month
pie_values = [[None,None]] * 12
for month in range (1,13):
    month_df = seller_earn_month_df[seller_earn_month_df.month == month]
    MAX_EARNS = month_df.earnings.sum()*BST_SLLR_RATE
    sum_earnings = 0
    index_75 = 0
    for index, row in month_df.iterrows():
        data.loc[data['sellerid'] == row.sellerid, 'best_seller'] = True
        sum_earnings += row.earnings
        index_75 += 1
        if sum_earnings > MAX_EARNS:
            pie_values[month-1] = [index_75,len(month_df.index)-index_75]
            break
# Number of elements with most sells per month
monthly_sum = seller_num_month_df.groupby(["month"]).sum().sells
for month in range (1,13):
    MAX_SELLS = monthly_sum.iloc[month-1]*BST_SLLR_RATE
    sum_sells = 0
    for index, row in seller_num_month_df[seller_num_month_df.month == month].iterrows():
        data.loc[data['sellerid'] == row.sellerid, 'best_seller'] = True
        sum_sells += row.sells
        if sum_sells > MAX_SELLS:
            break

del month_df, MAX_EARNS, sum_earnings, index_75, monthly_sum, MAX_SELLS, sum_sells

# Tokenize title
stop = set(stopwords.words('spanish'))
def tokenize(text):
    try: 
        regex = re.compile('[' +re.escape(string.punctuation) + '0-9\\r\\t\\n]')
        text = regex.sub(" ", text) # remove punctuation
        tokens_ = [word_tokenize(s) for s in sent_tokenize(text)]
        tokens = []
        for token_by_sent in tokens_:
            tokens += token_by_sent
        tokens = list(filter(lambda t: t.lower() not in stop, tokens))
        filtered_tokens = [w for w in tokens if re.search('[a-zA-Z]', w)]
        filtered_tokens = [w.lower() for w in filtered_tokens if len(w)>=3]
        return filtered_tokens
    except TypeError as e: print(text,e)
        
data['tokens'] = data['title'].map(tokenize)
data.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

# PLOT: Generate WordCloud
def generate_wordcloud(tup):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color='white',
                          max_words=50, max_font_size=40,
                          random_state=42
                         ).generate(str(tup))
    return wordcloud


cat_sllrs = dict()
for best in [True,False]: 
    text = " ".join(data.loc[data['best_seller']==best, 'title'].values)
    cat_sllrs[best] = tokenize(text)

best_sellers = Counter(cat_sllrs[True]).most_common(100)
worst_sellers = Counter(cat_sllrs[False]).most_common(100)

fig,axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(30, 15))

ax = axes[0]
ax.imshow(generate_wordcloud(best_sellers), interpolation="bilinear")
ax.axis('off')
ax.set_title("Best Sellers", fontsize=30)

ax = axes[1]
ax.imshow(generate_wordcloud(worst_sellers))
ax.axis('off')
ax.set_title("Worst Sellers", fontsize=30)

# FEATURE ENG: Keras Tokenizer for title feature
raw_text = data.title.str.lower()
tok_raw = Tokenizer(num_words=20000,
                    filters='!"#$%&()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~\t\n',
                    lower=True,
                    split=" ",
                    char_level=False)
tok_raw.fit_on_texts(raw_text)
data["seq_title"] = tok_raw.texts_to_sequences(data.title.str.lower())

del raw_text, tok_raw
